Summary
This paper studies the trustworthiness of current large language models in cross-lingual settings, focusing on clinical dialogue summarization for Indian languages. The paper mainly presents a practical empirical study rather than methodological innovation. The authors evaluate two 7B-scale open-source LLMs under multiple settings including zero-shot, few-shot, translation-based summarization, and supervised fine-tuning. The paper provides detailed analyses on hallucination, safety, and cross-lingual performance gaps across different language families.

Strengths
The paper studies an important and practical problem: the reliability and safety of LLMs in multilingual healthcare applications, which could affect a very large user population.
The empirical study is overall comprehensive and well organized. The analysis of hallucination and safety issues is useful and practically relevant.
Weaknesses
The experimental scope is somewhat limited. The paper only evaluates two 7B models, which makes it difficult to know whether the conclusions generalize to stronger or larger-scale LLMs.
There are several minor writing issues throughout the paper. For example:
some commas should be replaced with periods (e.g., line 177),
some model names could be abbreviated for readability (e.g., lines 230 and 231).

Summary
This paper considers the robust summarization of clinical doctor-patient dialogues from multilingual Indian languages. The paper explores various methodologies for this task across languages from different typological language families. It considers zero-shot summarization, in-context-learning-based summarization, translation-based summarization, and supervised fine-tuning. The empirical results evaluate two open-source models using a variety of metrics, including safety, trustworthiness, explainability (based on LLM judges), and entity extraction (based on an LLM evaluator). The paper demonstrates some key empirical findings: supervised fine-tuning generally produces the best results across the considered settings; low-resource languages, such as Dravidian languages, produce worse results for language models trained heavily on Latin-script languages; and safety is the hardest metric to improve.

Strengths
Considers a problem that is highly relevant to the robust deployment of open-source LLMs in a safety-critical domain.
Presents a substantial empirical study across a variety of metrics involving robustness and accuracy of LLMs on clinical summarization, comparing various Indian languages, which is an important but understudied problem.
Weaknesses
There is not much technical novelty; the work is mainly an application of existing techniques to an under-explored problem.
There is an over-reliance on the judgement provided by a single model, GPT-4o, for many of the important evaluations, including safety and entity extraction. Although the paper considers some human evaluation of the results, this does not cover all aspects of the evaluation.
Although the paper provides a reference to the considered dataset, further details should be mentioned, such as the number of examples for each language type, the length of the conversations, and the details of the summaries. Preferably, the tests should also be run with multiple random seeds, and the results should be averaged. However, this is not mentioned and is not clear from the text.
The page limits have not been maintained.

This paper presents an empirical study of open-source LLMs for cross-lingual clinical dialogue summarization across ten Indian languages. The task is to generate English structured clinical summaries from multilingual doctor-patient conversations. The paper evaluates two 7B-parameter models, Mistral-7B-Instruct and Qwen2.5-7B-Instruct, under four settings: zero-shot prompting, few-shot prompting, translate-then-summarize, and LoRA-based supervised fine-tuning. The evaluation combines lexical/semantic metrics, LLM-as-judge scores for truthfulness, safety, and explainability, and LLM-based clinical entity-level analysis using precision, recall, hallucination rate, omission rate, and entity (F1). The entity-level analysis is relevant because it goes beyond surface text similarity, but it also depends on GPT-4o-mini for entity extraction, normalization, and semantic comparison, making it similar in nature to the LLM-as-judge evaluation.

The paper is a good fit for RobustifAI because it studies an important deployment robustness problem: whether clinical summarization systems remain reliable in multilingual and low-resource settings. Its main contribution is a systematic empirical comparison showing that few-shot prompting and translation can degrade performance, while supervised fine-tuning improves entity-level accuracy and reduces hallucination.

Strengths
The paper addresses an important and underexplored robustness problem: trustworthy clinical summarization in multilingual and low-resource Indian language settings.
The topic is well aligned with the workshop’s focus on robustifying GenAI systems, especially operational robustness and deployment reliability.
The study compares multiple practical deployment strategies, including zero-shot prompting, few-shot prompting, translation, and supervised fine-tuning.
The evaluation goes beyond lexical metrics and includes clinical entity-level hallucination and omission analysis.
The negative findings are valuable: few-shot prompting and translation can degrade performance, which is important for practitioners.
The paper is generally well motivated and the main contribution is easy to identify.
The finding that supervised fine-tuning reduces hallucination and narrows cross-lingual disparities is significant.
The observation that safety remains difficult to improve, even after fine-tuning, is important for robust clinical GenAI deployment.
Weaknesses and concerns
The work is primarily an empirical study using existing methods, so the methodological originality is limited. The contribution is mainly in the evaluation setting and analysis.

Heavy reliance on LLM-as-a-judge evaluation. A small human evaluation is included, but it covers only four languages and the visible table shows only Marathi and Tamil examples, not a full rigorous validation study.

The summary format, prompts are not sufficiently specified. The paper refers to a ``structured clinical summary'' and says full prompts appear in Appendix 10, but the submitted PDF does not appear to include the exact summary template, generation prompts, LLM-as-judge prompts, entity extraction prompts, or rubrics. This limits reproducibility and makes the LLM-based evaluation harder to assess.

The translation approach would benefit from a more explicit analysis of translation quality.

Direct cross-lingual summarization asks the model to both understand and translate the source dialogue and summarize it in English. The paper should discuss more explicitly how this combined translation-plus-summarization burden affects performance compared with summarization only pipelines.

The English baseline is included but could be compared and discussed more consistently as a reference point for the multilingual conditions.

Some tables and figures are not discussed sufficiently in the text.

Table 2’s color coding is unclear. The caption says green indicates the best value per row and red the worst value per row, but several rows appear to highlight best/worst values separately within each model family rather than globally across all eight conditions.

There appear to be formatting/page-limit issues. The paper seems to exceed the 7-page limit by several lines, and Table 10 is referenced in the main text but appears outside the main page limit. The appendix/human evaluation section also appears incorrectly positioned, possibly due to a LaTeX compilation issue.

There are also internal consistency and editing problems. For example, the heading “When In-Context Learning Fails (what about this?” appears unfinished. Some references are incomplete such as the "What Makes In-Context Learning Work" entry.
